{
    "level": "A2–B1",
    "intro": "In this chapter, you will learn to <strong>distinguish between the main ways of talking about the future</strong> and choose the form depending on meaning.",
    "rules": [
        {
            "label": "WILL",
            "color": "blue",
            "text": "Spontaneous decisions, promises, requests, neutral predictions:",
            "example": "I'll help you. / I think it will rain."
        },
        {
            "label": "BE GOING TO",
            "color": "emerald",
            "text": "Plans and predictions based on what is seen now:",
            "example": "I'm going to call her. Look at those clouds! meanings:"
        },
        {
            "label": "KEY IDEA",
            "color": "amber",
            "text": "Питай себе: це рішення зараз, уже готовий план чи висновок із доказу?",
            "example": "moment now / plan before / evidence now"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "Що входить у розділ",
    "intro": "Майбутні форми покривають кілька типових значень:",
    "rows": [
        {
            "en": "Will",
            "ua": "spontaneous decision, promise, opinion",
            "note": "I'll answer it. / I think she will arrive. rain."
        },
        {
            "en": "Be going to",
            "ua": "намір або план, що вже існує",
            "note": "We're going to move house."
        },
        {
            "en": "Be going to",
            "ua": "передбачення на основі доказу",
            "note": "It's going to rain."
        },
        {
            "en": "Choice of form",
            "ua": "choice depends on meaning, not only time",
            "note": "same future idea, different reason"
        }
    ],
    "warning": "💡 In the future forms, it is important not only "when?", but also "why this particular form?"."
}

{
    "title": "What to pay attention to",
    "items": [
        "If the decision arose <strong>right now</strong>, we usually choose <strong>will</strong>.",
        "If the plan was <strong>before the moment of speech</strong>, usually we choose <strong>be going to</strong>.",
        "If it is an <strong>opinion or assumption</strong> without direct evidence, we often use <strong>will</strong>.",
        "If there is <strong>visible evidence</strong> now, we often use <strong>be going to</strong>."
    ]
}
